al philosophy of laissez-faire but fearing authoritarianism, these writers sought out forms of social solidarity closer than individualism admitted but freer than collectivism allowed. They discovered such solidarities while teaching economics, history, and literature to workers in the north of England and elsewhere. They wrote histories of capitalism to make these solidarities articulate. They used makeshift languages of “tradition” and “custom” to describe them until Thompson patented the idea of the “moral economy.” Their program began as a way of theorizing everything economics left out, but in challenging utilitarian orthodoxy in economics from the outside, they anticipated the work of later innovators inside economics.Examining the moral cornerstones of a twentieth-century critique of capitalism, The Moral Economists explains why this critique fell into disuse, and how it might be reformulated for the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCapitalismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aCapitalism. 0aKapitalismus. 0aKritik. 0aSocialism. 0aThompson, E. P. (Edward Palmer), 1924-1993. 0aWirtschaftsethik. 0aÖkonomische Ideengeschichte. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAdult education.  aAmartya Sen.  aAntipathy.  aAuthoritarianism.  aCalculation.  aCambridge University Press.  aCapitalism.  aChristian left.  aChristian socialism.  aCollectivism.  aCommunism.  aCorporatism.  aCriticism of capitalism.  aCriticism.  aCritique.  aDetermination.  aDouble Movement.  aE. P. Thompson.  aEconomic history.  aEconomic problem.  aEconomics.  aEconomism.  aEconomist.  aEric Hobsbawm.  aEthics.  aEvan Durbin.  aForm of life (philosophy).  aGraham Wallas.  aGuild socialism.  aGyörgy Lukács.  aHomo economicus.  aHostility.